column3: Upton Sinclair strengthens his argument that conditions were unsanitary in meat processing factories through describing the various ways in which workers would use or cover up spoiled meat. This included suppressing the odor through the use of borax and glycerin, adding more meat to cover the spoiled meat, filling hams with pickle, chopping spoiled meat to make "sausage", selling bad hams as "Number Three Grade", and through extracting the bone of bad ham and selling it as boneless ham. Since spoiled meat had a very strong odor to it, workers within factories had to ensure that consumers would not be able to smell it so that they would be more likely to buy and consume it. As a result, they used sweet smelling or odorless products in order to mask the stench. Hams were pickled with a machine that was both quick and effective, but would sometimes spoil the meat further. This detail further helped to support Sinclair's claim that factories mainly cared about making a profit rather than the health of their consumers. Additionally, factory workers used methods of hiding or covering up spoiled meat by making it more subtle through covering it with unspoiled meat or chopping it into smaller pieaces so it would go unnoticed by consumers. Lastly, Sinclair describes how spoiled ham was especially covered up through selling bad ham as "Number Three Grade" or "smoked ham". Later however, "they would extract the bone, about which the bad part generally lay, and insert in the hole a white-hot iron" (Sinclair 1906). This would eliminate the title of "Number Three Grade" in favor of "boneless ham".
column4: I have reworded the passage as follows:  Upton Sinclair argues that conditions in meat processing factories were unsanitary due to the various ways employed by workers to cover up spoiled meat. These measures not only concealed the smell of spoiled meat but also ensured that consumers would be unable to detect it. Workers employed several techniques to disguise spoiled meat, including using borax and glycerin to supress the odor, adding more meat to cover it, stuffing hams with pickle, chopping spoiled meat to create sausage, selling bad hams as "Number Three Grade," and extracting the bone of spoiled ham and inserting it into the hole to eliminate the title. These practices highlight the hypocrisy of meat processing factories' pursuit of profit over the well-being of their consumers.

column3: The ideal tragedy, according to Aristotle, has many complex elements which excite pity and fear among the characters and audience. According to the text, "It should, moreover, imitate actions which excite pity and fear, this being the distinctive mark of tragic imitation... it possesses no single tragic quality; it neither satisfies the moral sense nor calls forth pity or fear." (Paragraph 2) As shown, the elements that make up the tragedy must contain moments of "pity and fear", to be recognized as a true tragedy. Also, the tragedy should arise from a mistake or error from the main character. The tragedy should, "come about as the result not of vice, but of some great error or frailty, in a character either such as we have described, or better rather than worse." (Paragraph 3) Lastly, the ideal tragedy shifts the mood from good to bad, most often ending the same way. The text says, "The change of fortune should be not from bad to good, but, reversely, from good to bad... this principle in his plays, many of which end unhappily. It is, as we have said, the right ending." (Paragraph 3) As described the ideal tragedy moves the plot from good to bad, which continues until the end of the play.
column4: Sure, here is the rewording you requested:    "A tragedy, according to Aristotle, is characterized by complexity and intrigue, sparking both pity and fear in the audience. It must feature actions that evoke these emotions, distinguishing it from mere imitation. A tragedy arises from a significant error committed by the main character, and it must fulfill certain requirements to be considered tragic, including the result not being caused by malice but by some form of frailty or error. Lastly, the tragic mood swings from good to bad, mirroring the shift in fortune that defines the tragic end."

column4: The ancient Egyptian system of government had a stratified pyramid structure, with each social class occupying a distinct place. The lowest level comprised slaves, workers, and individuals with poor living conditions, often found at the base of the pyramid. The second level housed farmers, scribes, and individuals with more modest resources. The third level consisted of merchants, shopkeepers, and individuals with relatively stable lives and some economic prosperity. The highest level was occupied by kings, priests, and individuals of significant wealth. Evidence supporting this hierarchy is provided in paragraph 6, showcasing that below the pharaohs, powerful nobles and priests were found at the top. Middle class individuals, including shopkeepers and scribes, occupied the middle segment of the pyramid. Notably, slaves and farmers and workers and scribes were situated at the bottom tier.
